it the whims and needs of individual communities.   In Recipes and Everyday Knowledge, Elaine Leong situates recipe knowledge and practices among larger questions of gender and cultural history, the history of the printed word, and the history of science, medicine, and technology. The production of recipes and recipe books, she argues, were at the heart of "idian investigations of the natural world or "household science". She shows how English homes acted as vibrant spaces for knowledge making and transmission, and explores how recipe trials allowed householders to gain deeper understandings of sickness and health, of the human body, and of natural and human-built processes. By recovering this story, Leong extends the parameters of natural inquiry and productively widens the cast of historical characters participating in and contributing to early modern science.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aFormulas, recipes, etczEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aHome economicszEnglandxHistoryy17th century. 0aMedicine, PopularxHistoryy17th century. 0aNote-takingxHistoryy17th century. 4aeveryday knowledge. 4agender and science. 4ahistory of experimentation. 4ahistory of knowledge. 4ahistory of medicine. 4ahistory of science. 4ahousehold science. 4amanuscript and print cultures. 4arecipes. 4asocial knowledge. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226583525423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226583525.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles